# Status Report Skill — Activation Guidance
 
## What this skill does
 
Turns messy delivery inputs into structured, honest stakeholder status reports.
Works across agile, project, programme, product, and hybrid contexts.
Adapts language to the input context and audience.
 
## When to use it
 
Use this skill when you have raw or semi-structured information about a team,
project, initiative, or release and need a clear stakeholder update.
 
**Typical trigger phrases**:
- "Write a status report from these notes"
- "Turn this into a stakeholder update"
- "Draft a status update for [exec/client/board/leadership]"
- "Here are my project notes — can you make a status report?"
- "I need to send an update on [project/initiative]"
- "Summarise project status for the sponsor"
- "Help me write a weekly update"
- "Here's the sprint summary and our blockers — can you format this?"
**Also use it when**:
- A user pastes team notes, meeting outputs, or a mix of delivery signals
- A user has a RAID log and needs it surfaced for stakeholders
- A user needs a client-facing version of an internal update
- A user is preparing for a programme board and needs a clean brief
## When NOT to use it
 
- When the user wants a retrospective analysis or lessons-learned document
  → Use the retro-analysis skill
- When the user wants a workshop synthesis
  → Use the workshop-analysis skill
- When the user wants a backlog refinement transcript analysed
  → Use the appropriate refinement skill
- When the user wants a sprint retrospective diagnostic
  → Use the retro-analysis skill
## What the skill produces
 
A six-section structured report:
1. Overall Status (with ON TRACK / AT RISK / OFF TRACK / UNKNOWN anchor)
2. Progress Since Last Update
3. Risks, Blockers, and Dependencies (with per-item confidence ratings)
4. Changes and Emerging Concerns
5. Next Steps and Recommended Actions
6. Confidence and Gaps
Plus a Signal Quality header that declares input quality and audience assumption.
 
## Deployment note for Claude Projects
 
Project instructions should contain only a brief activation statement.
All skill logic lives in the SKILL.md and reference files.
 
**Suggested Project instruction**:
```
When the user asks for a status report, stakeholder update, or delivery summary,
use the status-report skill. Read SKILL.md before generating any output.
```
 
Do not duplicate skill logic in the Project instruction.
 
